some people might not know much about spirits, right? I'm a little biased because I live in

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:55.080
Kentucky, and here everybody knows about bourbon, because it's the famous saying that there are more

00:12:55.080 --> 00:13:01.239
you know barrels of bourbon than there are Kentuckians. Well, when you make a whiskey

00:13:01.239 --> 00:13:04.760
or bourbon, you make a distillate, and you put it in a barrel. And if you've never seen one of

00:13:04.760 --> 00:13:09.640
these barrels, they're really big. They hold about 55 gallons of liquid. And then they go into a

00:13:09.640 --> 00:13:14.119
warehouse, and when they're full, they weigh about 500 pounds. And they sit in a warehouse for

00:13:15.080 --> 00:13:21.400
you know, four to 12 to even longer years. And of course, due to evaporation and soakage and

00:13:22.039 --> 00:13:28.200
maybe issues with barrels, you're going to have some amount of liquid left in that barrel whenever

00:13:28.200 --> 00:13:34.520
you go to dump it. And as you might imagine, especially if you're in finance, you know,

00:13:34.520 --> 00:13:39.080
a couple percent changes in that amount, that's a big deal. I mean, that's product that you thought

00:13:39.080 --> 00:13:46.760
you would have that you don't have. So using some cool data science methods to get data from places

00:13:46.760 --> 00:13:51.400
that I wouldn't have really expected, to feed that into models that can help predict what yields are

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:56.440
going to be, was something I didn't think would work, but that did. And that's a really cool

00:13:56.440 --> 00:14:04.599
