Yeah, so I like tidy models. I like the framework there. Actually, I came up in Basar. So if I'm

00:14:48.840 --> 00:14:54.119
doing like a logistic regression or a linear model, I mean, I got to be honest, oftentimes

00:14:54.119 --> 00:14:57.960
I'll make it out quickly in Basar before I move on to like a tidy models framework.

00:14:58.520 --> 00:15:03.559
For like machine learning and deep learning, I use the Keras and TensorFlow packages.

00:15:05.479 --> 00:15:09.719
That's what we have in production now for the models that we're using. And stepping out a bit

00:15:09.719 --> 00:15:13.719
from machine learning, the tidyverse is always like the first thing that I call pretty much

00:15:13.719 --> 00:15:19.799
everything that I'm doing. I live in our markdown. I think that unless you're doing something that's

00:15:19.799 --> 00:15:25.239
very, very small and one-off, you should almost always start your work at our markdown. Because

00:15:25.239 --> 00:15:28.919
the point of the work you're doing is probably going to be to communicate something. And you're

00:15:28.919 --> 00:15:32.520
going to end up doing double work. You're going to probably write a script, and then maybe you

00:15:32.520 --> 00:15:37.880
would open, God forbid, Word or something like that to make a report while you're writing your

00:15:37.880 --> 00:15:43.960
code. But if you come with that in mind, you can open our markdown, start it off as a report,

00:15:43.960 --> 00:15:49.320
do your analytical work, organize it. And at the end of the day, you've pushed a button.

00:15:49.320 --> 00:15:54.119
You have a beautiful HTML web page with a floating table of contents, code chunks that

00:15:54.119 --> 00:15:59.799
fold in and out. You can also use Python, or R, or SQL, or D3, or other languages within those

00:15:59.799 --> 00:16:03.880
chunks. And then if you have team, you can push button to host that to team, shoot someone a URL.

00:16:03.880 --> 00:16:09.559
And now you have a one source of truth hosted report that anyone can go to that you can control

00:16:09.559 --> 00:16:14.919
access to. And you did all that in one markdown script. So our markdown is just completely

00:16:14.919 --> 00:16:19.960
invaluable for the work that I do. We're actually looking at trying to take some of our ETL work

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:26.359
directly into a markdown-based, like a notebook-based format, just because the documentation

00:16:26.359 --> 00:16:30.919
and the scheduling and all that kind of comes along for the ride whenever you do that work.

00:16:32.039 --> 00:16:37.239
I like Shiny a lot, but I'm also a big fan of Flex Dashboard because it's really lightweight. It's

00:16:37.239 --> 00:16:43.080
really fast. You can write your reactive code right there instead of kind of having

00:16:43.080 --> 00:16:47.000
code in the server and then referring to that code in the UI. If it's something small,

00:16:47.320 --> 00:16:53.640
something very quick, I mean, I can go from nothing to a hosted Flex Dashboard with reactives

00:16:53.640 --> 00:16:58.200
in like an hour and a half. And so if I need something very fast, I will use that. The other

00:16:58.200 --> 00:17:02.679
really cool thing about Flex Dashboard is if you're not using reactivity, you can actually,

00:17:02.679 --> 00:17:07.160
and you don't have a way to host applications to sort of show the value of what you're doing,

00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:12.280
you can email the resulting knitted HTML of a Flex Dashboard to someone. And when they open it,

00:17:12.280 --> 00:17:16.199
it opens like a beautiful webpage that's interactive for them. And that's a really

00:17:16.199 --> 00:17:20.520
cool way to share content if you don't yet have the ability to publish and host up. And I actually

00:17:20.520 --> 00:17:25.160
took advantage of that at Brown for Ormond to try to show people what you can do with our tools.

